      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":10,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"20 min easy run at 5:58/km — your physiotherapist-cleared pace. Start with a 5-min walk warm-up. If any foot pain arises, shift to walk/run intervals (2 min run, 1 min walk). This is your foundation session for the week.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"20 min easy run at 5:58/km. Focus on feel — relaxed breathing, soft foot strike. Walk breaks are always on the table if your foot talks to you. No heroics needed here.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"Your long run day — still capped at 20 min easy at 5:58/km per physio clearance. Think of this as your anchor session. Same walk-break rule applies. The goal is consistency, not distance.\"},{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest. Let the adaptation happen — this is where fitness is actually built.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Your plantar fascia needs time between loading sessions. This is an active investment in Saturday's run.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Optional: 20–30 min low-impact cross-training (swimming, cycling, or upper-body strength). Zero foot loading. Skip entirely if fatigue is high — this is a bonus, not a requirement.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest before Saturday's long run. Keep it easy — a short walk is fine, but save your legs for tomorrow.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome back, James. This first week is about re-establishing your rhythm with three easy runs, all within your physiotherapist's 20-minute clearance window. Your recent training history shows you've been building steadily and handling 5:58/km well — that's a genuinely solid foundation to work from. The weekly target of ~10 km reflects where your body is right now, not where it's been. No speed work, no pushing the ceiling — just consistent, pain-free time on your feet. The optional Thursday cross-train gives you a cardiovascular outlet without loading the plantar fascia. Pay attention to how your foot feels in the first 5 minutes of each run (you've noticed morning stiffness before), and don't hesitate to use walk breaks — they're a tool, not a setback. What's your sense of how the foot has been feeling day-to-day heading into this week?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
